3. About Nancy Eileen Boycan
Vital statistics:

Born: October 26, 1942, Butler, PA
Raised: West Sunbury, PA (rural)
Died: May 2, 2025, Virginia Hospital Center, Arlington, VA — age 82
Lived in Reston, VA (1409 Greenmont Court) from 1973
Cause of death: MRSA endocarditis contracted while hospitalized for blood sugar/insulin episode, while undergoing treatment for Stage 4 neuroendocrine carcinoma
Disposition: Cremation, Carewell Cremations, Fairfax VA

Parents: Kenneth Irwin Weisenstein and Ina Catherine Weisenstein (both deceased)

Siblings:

Ronald Weisenstein (sons: Ron and Eric Weisenstein)
Kenneth Weisenstein (wife: Gretchen; daughters: Kathy Weisenstein Cummings, Barbara [last name TBD], Sharon Eisnor [confirm spelling])

Former husband: Gary Boycan (married 1965, divorced 1976, remained lifelong friends; visited Nancy on her deathbed)

Sons:

Steven Thomas Boycan, Scotch Plains NJ — daughter: Eloise Krystyna Boycan
David Scott Boycan, Arlington VA — wife: Murrin McClafferty; children: Brendan, Connor, Alison, Nathan

Education:

Grove City College [major TBD]
Virginia Polytechnic Institute (Virginia Tech) — MS [field TBD] via graduate fellowship

Career: Systems engineer and program manager, defense industry

Employers: Sperry → E-Systems → Space Station Program Office → MITRE Corporation → co-owner boutique defense contracting firm, Northern Virginia
Specialties: SIGINT, Electronic Warfare, naval defense programs, early UAV/unmanned systems
Notable: Believed to be one of the first (if not the first) woman to go to sea on an operational U.S. Navy vessel for acceptance testing of a classified program
Health interruption: Diagnosed with Chronic Fatigue Syndrome and Diabetes mid-career, sidelined for several years, returned to work
Also operated a Floor Covering International franchise in Florida

Personal:

Shy by nature but wanted people around her; deep lifelong friendships over many acquaintances
Loved animals (birds especially, also snakes/lizards/insects — would not harm them)
Dogs: "Fluffy/Killer" (stray), Fritz (colleague's schnauzer), Dexter (David's lab), Brindle (Bruce's dog)
Longtime companion: Bruce (Lusby, MD); enjoyed fishing Patuxent River/Chesapeake Bay, crabs, firepits
Loved the beach, waves at night; took boys to Bahamas/Acapulco/Hawaii; Bahamas timeshare 1980s–early 90s; danced Junkanoo
Music: Neil Diamond, Gordon Lightfoot, Beatles, Simon & Garfunkel, Linda Ronstadt, Elvis, Elton John, Santana, ELO, Beach Boys, Cyndi Lauper, Queen, Barbara Streisand, ABBA, Taylor Swift — danced in the aisle at Mamma Mia on Broadway
Cooking: hospitality rule (always feed guests no matter the hour), holiday meal traditions (raisin stuffing Thanksgiving, ham/turkey Christmas, corned beef St. Patrick's, ham & scalloped potatoes Easter), same-day corn on the cob, chile parties
Generous: took in renters in need, gave to people on the street
Faith: spiritually Protestant Christian, unaffiliated; Presbyterian upbringing, Lutheran extended family; crosses/religious images in home
Final wishes: be celebrated not mourned; memorial party; ashes in a trout stream

Health timeline (final illness):

2024: Diagnosed Stage 4 neuroendocrine carcinoma (aggressive)
Chemotherapy Round 1: Strong response
Clinical immunotherapy trial: Partial remission
Adverse reaction to immunotherapy: Had to stop
Preparing for Chemo Round 2 when collapsed from blood sugar/insulin episode
Hospitalized → contracted MRSA → MRSA infected heart valve (endocarditis)
Doctors recommended hospice — Nancy refused
Treatments for infection incompatible with chemotherapy; cascade of systemic failures
Passed May 2, 2025, with son Steven at her side


